messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

Analysis summary:
- The endpoint is defined in app/api/cms/user.py at get_allowed_apis with route("/permissions") under the user blueprint.
- The user blueprint is registered under cms with url_prefix="/cms", and cms itself is registered with url_prefix="/cms" in app/api/cms/__init__.py. Therefore, the full path is "/cms/user/permissions".
- The route decorator did not specify HTTP methods, so Flask defaults to GET only. There is no explicit allowance for other methods in the code.
- HEAD and OPTIONS are typically handled automatically by Flask for routes that support GET, but this behavior is framework-level, not explicitly coded in this endpoint.

Results:
- Full HTTP request path: /cms/user/permissions
- All HTTP methods acceptable: False
- HEAD acceptable: True (Flask will automatically handle HEAD for a GET endpoint)
- POST acceptable: False
- OPTIONS acceptable: True (Flask will automatically handle OPTIONS for the endpoint)
- TRACE acceptable: False
- GET acceptable: True
- PUT acceptable: False
- DELETE acceptable: False
- PATCH acceptable: False

Explanation:
- The route is defined as @user_api.route("/permissions") with no methods specified, so the endpoint supports only GET by default.
- Flask automatically provides HEAD and OPTIONS for routes that support GET, so both HEAD and OPTIONS are effectively acceptable, even though not explicitly declared in the code.
- All other HTTP methods (POST, PUT, DELETE, PATCH, TRACE) are not supported by this endpoint as they are not declared or handled in the code.
- The path /cms/user/permissions reflects the nested blueprints: cms has prefix "/cms" and user has prefix "/user". There are no path parameters in this endpoint.
